<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="UTF-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>Geotechnical Engineering in Overland Park</title><meta name="description" content="Professional soil mechanics study in Overland Park backed by ASTM D1586, D2487, and IBC standards. We deliver lab"><link rel="canonical" href="https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/"><meta property="og:type" content="website"><meta property="og:title" content="Geotechnical Engineering in Overland Park"><meta property="og:description" content="Professional soil mechanics study in Overland Park backed by ASTM D1586, D2487, and IBC standards. We deliver lab"><meta property="og:url" content="https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/"><meta property="og:site_name" content="Geotechnical Engineering"><meta property="og:locale" content="en_US"><meta property="og:image" content="https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/img/estudio-mecanica-suelos-1.webp"><meta property="og:image:width" content="1200"><meta property="og:image:height" content="630"><meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image"><meta name="twitter:title" content="Geotechnical Engineering in Overland Park"><meta name="twitter:description" content="Professional soil mechanics study in Overland Park backed by ASTM D1586, D2487, and IBC standards. We deliver lab and field data for safe foundations in Johnson County soils."><meta name="twitter:image" content="https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/img/estudio-mecanica-suelos-1.webp">
<script type="application/ld+json">{"@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [{"@type": "LocalBusiness", "@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#org-4b3a", "name": "Overland Park", "url": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/", "email": "contact@geotechnical-engineering.xyz", "address": {"@type": "PostalAddress", "addressLocality": "Overland Park", "addressCountry": "USA"}, "geo": {"@type": "GeoCoordinates", "latitude": 38.9743, "longitude": -94.6852}, "areaServed": {"@type": "City", "name": "Overland Park"}}, {"@type": "Service", "@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#service-4b3a", "serviceType": "Soil mechanics study", "name": "Geotechnical Engineering in Overland Park", "description": "Professional soil mechanics study in Overland Park backed by ASTM D1586, D2487, and IBC standards. We deliver lab and field data for safe foundations in Johnson County soils.", "provider": {"@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#org-4b3a"}, "areaServed": {"@type": "City", "name": "Overland Park"}, "url": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/"}, {"@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/", "url": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/", "name": "Geotechnical Engineering in Overland Park", "inLanguage": "en", "isPartOf": {"@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#website-4b3a"}}, {"@type": "WebSite", "@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#website-4b3a", "url": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/", "name": "Overland Park", "inLanguage": "en"}, {"@type": "FAQPage", "@id": "https://overland-park.geotechnical-engineering.xyz/#faq-4b3a", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "How much does a soil mechanics study cost for a typical Overland Park residential lot?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "For a standard single-family lot in Johnson County, a soil mechanics study generally runs between US$3,090 and US$4,940. The final number depends on the number of borings, whether consolidation or triaxial testing is required, and how deep the competent bearing stratum sits."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Which ASTM standards apply to a soil mechanics study in Kansas?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The core standards are ASTM D1586 for the Standard Penetration Test, ASTM D2487 for soil classification, and ASTM D2435 for consolidation. Seismic site class follows ASCE 7-22 Chapter 20, and the lab program typically includes ASTM D4318 for Atterberg limits and ASTM D3080 for direct shear."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How deep do borings need to go in Overland Park to satisfy the IBC?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "IBC 2021 Section 1803 requires borings to extend through unsuitable material and at least 5 feet into competent bearing strata. In Overland Park, where shale bedrock often appears between 15 and 30 feet, we typically core 5 to 10 feet into the rock to confirm it is not just a boulder or a thin ledge, and we go deeper if the load is column-supported on drilled piers."}}]}]}</script>
